<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Money Markets: High Lombard lending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONDITIONS in the German cash market remained extremely tight yesterday as
banks continued to borrow through the very expensive Lombard facility to
meet end-of-month requirements, writes James Blitz.
The problems encountered in last week's very illiquid market continued to
haunt dealers.
There had been very little borrowing in last Wednesday's regular money
market oper-ations on the assumption that official rates would come down.
When rates stayed unchanged on Thursday, dealers found themselves short at a
time when they needed to have books balanced to meet end-of-month
requirements.
Some DM6.3bn was therefore borrowed at the rate of 7.75 per cent on Monday,
and heavy Lombard borrowing was reported yesterday. Call money was traded at
a very wide spread of 7.25 per cent to 7.75 per cent. Three-month money
remained at 6.55 per cent.
The Bundesbank announced a repo rate for today's weekly operations at 6.80
per cent for maturities of 14 days. This was no surprise to a market which
has become increasingly scep-tical about the possibility of German rate cuts
being made in the next four weeks.
September Euromark futures declined 3 basis points to close at 93.43, coming
more and more into line with the cash level.
There is similar downward pressure on the front-month French franc
contracts.
Yesterday, the September French franc contract fell 6 basis points to finish
at 92.86. But at this level it is pricing three-month cash in two weeks'
time at 7.14 per cent, some 35 basis points below yesterday's cash level.
Dealers are pricing in more reductions in French rates.
One dealer wondered how likely further easing was, with the French franc at
the comparatively strong FFr3.49 to the D-Mark, and with a pronounced
downside.
Conditions in the sterling market were extremely tight yesterday, with a
Pounds 2.15bn shortage forecast by the Bank of England and no takers in the
early round of trading.
The overnight rate conse-quently came near to the 8 per cent level, and
three-month money nudged up to 5 29/32 per cent, having been at 5 7/8 per
cent at the end of last week. The September short sterling contract weakened
4 basis points to 94.11. The December contract was also down 4 points,
finishing at 94.56.
</TEXT>
