<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / International Company News: Litton Inds wins Dollars 1.2bn
suit against Honeywell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A LOS ANGELES jury yesterday awarded Litton Industries, the Californian high
technology group, Dollars 1.2bn for the alleged infringement of a patent by
Honeywell, the Minnesota-based controls company. But Honeywell pointed out
that the judge was continuing to hear evidence in the case, which it
insisted was far from over.
The jury's award is very high by the standard of patent cases and could hurt
Honeywell's shares when the New York Stock Exchange begins trading this
morning.
The stock of both companies was suspended ahead of yesterday afternoon's
announcement and trading did not resume later in the day.
The case centres on ring laser gyroscopes, a device used in aircraft
navigation, which Honeywell pioneered in the 1960s.
Litton alleges that Honeywell infringed its patents, taken out in 1979 and
1989, for a process to coat mirrors used as part of the gyroscope's
measuring system.
Honeywell argues that Litton's patents are invalid and Honeywell's coating
process is anyway different from that of its rival.
</TEXT>
