<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Astec (BSR) doubles to Pounds 4.33m -
Strong performance prompts resumption of dividend payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ASTEC (BSR), the Hong Kong-based and London-listed electronics company that
is 48.9 per cent owned by Emerson Electric of the US, is resuming dividend
payments for the first time in three years following a doubling of pre-tax
profits and earnings per share in the first half.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to June 27 jumped from Pounds 2.17m to
Pounds 4.33m, boosted, said Mr Brian Christopher, chairman, by higher sales,
a profits turnround in the slimmed-down electronic components division and
lower interest payments.
Sales increased by 9.6 per cent to Pounds 136.4m (Pounds 124.4m). On a
comparable basis, adjusting for exchange rate differences and operations
sold or closed in 1992, sales grew by 6.3 per cent.
The group, which has achieved a steady improvement in performance over the
past 18 months, reported increased earnings per share of 1.2p (0.6p).
It is paying an interim dividend of 0.25p, the first distribution since a
0.7p interim in 1990.
Mr George Tamke, chief executive, said the results reflected the company's
strong underlying financial performance, including growing market share and
improving operating margins.
Sales in the core power conversion business increased by almost 30 per cent
to Pounds 108m (Pounds 83.1m). However, after adjusting for the impact of
exchange rates the increase was a more modest 8.6 per cent.
Operating profits in the division increased to Pounds 3.9m (Pounds 3.6m) but
margins fell to 3.6 per cent (4.2 per cent) reflecting the non-recurring
start-up costs of a new modular production line and the group's second plant
in China.
Excluding these start-up costs, Mr Tamke said operating margins grew by a
percentage point.
Electronic components sales declined to Pounds 28.4m (Pounds 41.3m)
reflecting the reorganisation of the operations which now solely comprise
Beckman Industrial. However, the components business reported an operating
profit of Pounds 712,000, or 2.5 per cent of sales, compared with a loss of
Pounds 354,000, and is now expected to resume growth.
The group generated a positive cash flow of Pounds 13.1m in the first half
that enabled it to eliminate borrowings and end the period with Pounds
300,000 net cash.
As a result of this and lower interest rates net interest payable fell from
Pounds 977,000 to Pounds 240,000.
</TEXT>
