<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Izetbegovic edges closer to Bosnian settlement: Progress may
be made on split into mini-states
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIA'S President Alija Izetbegovic last night appeared to leave the door
open to a settlement with his Serb and Croat adversaries which could end the
17-month conflict in Bosnia.
After 12 hours of talks in Geneva, where peace talks resumed after 11 days,
Mr Izetbegovic told reporters that progress could be made today on agreeing
on a map to split the republic into three mini-states. But, in contrast to
more upbeat statements from Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, he
said: 'We have only discussed. No real progress so far. Maybe tomorrow.'
Mr Karadzic had appeared earlier to step up pressure on Mr Izetbegovic to
endorse a settlement today. He said: 'The negotiations are finished . . . we
expect the Moslems to sign the whole package tomorrow.'
While the two leaders appeared closer to an agreement, neither commented on
whether they had agreed to make changes in the proposed map. UN officials
played down the significance of an earlier announcement by Serb officials
that Serbs and Moslems had reached a five-point deal which included a
ceasefire and an early exchange of prisoners.
Meanwhile, in another sign of gathering momentum in the peace process,
western diplomats indicated that discussions were being stepped up for the
possible deployment of peacekeeping troops in the area.
Mr Manfred Worner, Nato secretary-general, is to meet Mr Boutros Boutros
Ghali, UN secretary-general, in Geneva today to discuss issues including
Bosnia. Nato officials in Brussels said the deployment of troops in Bosnia
was likely to be the central topic, but warned that the allies were still
not prepared to make any firm commitment yet on the numbers of troops.
However, the Russian government yesterday pledged to provide extra
peacekeeping troops for Bosnia in the event of a peace settlement between
the three warring factions, the first major power to do so unconditionally.
Speaking to reporters after meeting Mr Boutros Ghali, Mr Andrei Kozyrev,
Russia's foreign minister, said the number of troops would depend on the
terms of the peace accord and what their tasks would be.
It is widely expected in Nato that the US will provide a large part of the
40,000-plus extra peacekeeping troops that international mediators say will
be required to police a partition.
British officials indicated that Britain was considering contributing
several thousand troops, but stressed that a decision on the scale of its
commitment could not be made until the three sides had reached a firm peace
agreement in Geneva.
Although the Bosnian Serbs have accepted the peace package it is unclear if
they have made more territorial concessions to the mainly Moslem republic,
which, under the plan, will form a union along with the Croat and Serb
republics. But Mr Karadzic has previously refused to hand over more land to
the Moslems.
The Bosnian Moslems fear they will be wedged between the two ethnic states,
at the mercy of their foes.
</TEXT>
