<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's BBC Prom is an all-Mozart affair. The chamber orchestra The English
Concert, conducted by Trevor Pinnock, plays two symphonies, the Paris (K297)
and the Prague (K504) and, in between, three sections from Mozart's Vespers
(K339): Dixit Dominus, Laudate Dominum, and Magnificat (7.30 Radio 3).
With an eye to the opening next week of the world championship chess match
between Gary Kasparov and Britain's Nigel Short, BBC2's On The Line
investigates the notoriously odd relationship between chess and politics in
Russia (8.30).
For the handful of people who were not rooted in front of the set when they
were first transmitted, C4 is repeating five of the Inspector Morse dramas,
starting with a story about the murder of a retired policeman (8.30). BBC2
begins a three part drama about politics, centred upon Lou Larson, a female
Labour MP who is heavily into battered women and women's centres, but has a
'passionate past' which, it is feared, may be discovered by the press.
Phyllis Logan plays Lou (9.25).
</TEXT>
