<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Pressures that stretch a thin blue line: The police and the
crime rate are back on the political agenda. The report by Sir Patrick
Sheehy urging radical changes to police employment has been attacked by
officers of all ranks while MPs and the public are calling for initiatives
against crime. FT writers sound out feelings in the city and in the country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS DOREEN McDonnell is 65, lives in a two-up, two-down terraced house near
Liverpool's Royal Seaforth container terminal and has been mugged twice in
broad daylight, once on a bus and once in the street.
She says she does not know what the Sheehy report is but has heard of moves
to end 'jobs for life' for police officers.
'It's totally wrong,' she said. 'They deserve their job security and early
pensions. They have to deal with crime and horrible people. I feel so much
better when I see a policeman in the street. They have always been good to
me and they really helped me face the world again after the muggings.'
But if the police were paid on performance criteria such as solving crime,
what happened to Mrs McDonnell might not help them score many points. A
couple were arrested for allegedly robbing Mrs McDonnell on the bus but she
failed to pick them out at an identity parade.
The other mugger was convicted, but no thanks to the police - a passing
motorist who saw the robbery made a citizen's arrest.
Nor did the police catch the men who mugged two of Mrs McDonnell's friends
from the local bingo hall, robbing one of her winnings and the other of her
pension. But police nevertheless scored highly with the victims for the
support, help and reassurance they gave.
It is this sort of attitude that gives the police comfort in their
opposition to the Sheehy report.
Apart from performance-related pay rises, Sheehy proposes lower starting
salaries and an end to overtime, abolition of three middle-management ranks,
fewer promotion prospects, less generous pensions and initial 10-year
contracts, renewable at five-year intervals.
At Copperas Hill police station, 140 police, including CID, cover the few
square miles of a Liverpool city centre with only 5,000 residents, but which
daily attracts more than 200,000 workers, shoppers, tourists and visitors.
The area includes 250 pubs and clubs with late-night drinks licences.
Policing the area can be dangerous. Comradeship is important and teamwork
essential.
Constable Mark Blundell, who joined from the building industry eight years
ago when he was 23, said his total pay would go down under Sheehy. 'Morale
would take a battering, especially if a colleague had so many more
performance points on his pay than you.' he said.
Superintendent Philip Joy is on a job-swap from his normal patch at
Llandudno, North Wales, and is in charge of Copperas Hill.
'It's the young constables I fear for,' he said. 'Many don't want to move
up. Others who are ambitious see opportunities threatened. I have been doing
staff appraisals here in the last two months and 10 per cent are talking
about changing their job because they fear for long-term security or
progress.'
Chief Inspector Ted Bennett, who is in day-to-day charge of operations at
Copperas Hill, feels especially vulnerable. Sheehy would abolish his rank -
together with those of deputy chief constable and chief superintendent - in
an attempt to streamline management and free resources to put more police on
the beat.
He is 51 and has 30 years' service. He wants to carry on to 55 but is afraid
the over-50s will be the first chopped in any slimming down.
Recruits under 22 get an annual salary of about Pounds 12,500 initially,
while those over 24 get nearly Pounds 14,800. Mr Jim Sharples, Merseyside's
chief constable, says this has improved the calibre of recruits and
attracted many graduates.
Sheehy would cut starting salaries to Pounds 10,500, which the Police
Federation - representing junior ranks - says is Pounds 200 less than
traffic wardens' starting pay, in spite of shiftwork and greater
responsibility and danger.
Mr Sharples likes the managerial streamlining and greater flexibility Sheehy
might bring, but is very unhappy about its long-term implications for
quality of personnel.
He said: 'You have to look at Sheehy as a package, but all the gains in
efficiency which might come from greater operational flexibility would be
lost if we substitute a form of institutionalised insecurity among police
officers.'
Sheehy has united the police of all ranks as nothing before. In the public
at large, however, there appears less demonstrable sympathy than for other
public servants.
What the police are relying on is the support of the so-called 'silent'
majority. By definition this is not vocal, although that is no fault of Mrs
McDonnell.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
