<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Link of jobs to growth queried
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICIES DESIGNED to increase the rate of economic growth in Europe will do
very little to cut unemployment, Mr Paul Ormerod, a former economics
director of the Henley Centre for Forecasting, says.
The problem of unemployment is a question 'not of economics, but of social
values and social relationships', he writes in a paper prepared for a
seminar on full employment in Europe to be held this week in Sussex.
Societies with low unemployment are characterised by high levels of 'social
cohesion'.
