<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Privatised prison plans attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT plans to extend the role of the private sector in the UK prison
service were yesterday attacked by the opposition, prison officers and penal
reform groups.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, will announce a 'strategy for future
private-sector involvement' tomorrow, barely a week after publication of a
critical report on the first privatised prison.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said that the Labour party would
resist further privatisation of prisons until there had been a proper
assessment of privatisations which had already taken place.
Mr Robert Maclennan, Liberal Democrat home affairs spokesman, said that it
was not yet clear that privately run prisons offered a genuine improvement
in the service.
Only two of the UK's 130 prisons have so far been privatised - Wolds remand
prison on Humberside and Blakenhurst in Hereford and Worcester. The contract
to run Strangeways prison in Manchester was put out to tender but the
contract was won by the in-house team.
Judge Stephen Tumim, the chief inspector of prisons, said last week that it
was impossible to determine the value for money of the privatisation
arrangements for the Wolds prison. He blamed weaknesses in the management
agreement and an absence of systems for checking financial aspects of the
contract.
Judge Tumim also attacked the 'lethargy' among the prison's inmates, who
were not encouraged to make good use of their time. These comments follow
controversy over recently leaked Home Office documents which suggested that
Mr Howard thought prisons were not 'austere' enough.
The Prison Officers' Association promised fierce opposition to any further
privatisation plans. Mr John Bartell, its chairman, said members would be
balloted on industrial action if more prisons were to be privatised.
Mr Adam Sampson of the Prison Reform Trust said that privatising existing
jails would fall foul of the European Community directive that protects the
jobs and conditions of staff whose work is contracted out.
However, Group 4, the private security company that manages Wolds, said it
would be happy to bid for existing prisons.
</TEXT>
