<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / EC urged to ease regional aid rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday launched its bid to win EC regional aid aimed at
areas hit by defence spending cuts.
It called on the European Commission to relax rules that prevent funds being
allocated to prosperous parts of the country, such as the south-west, where
the decline in military orders has led to large job losses.
Submitting an outline bid for Pounds 15m of EC aid, the government said some
parts of Britain worst hit by defence cuts might not qualify for aid if the
Commission applied its structural funds objectives.
These objectives restrict aid spending to areas of industrial decline or
rural regions which need modernisation. The government is concerned that
adherence to the rules would mean counties such as Avon, where an estimated
7,000 defence-related jobs have been lost in the past six years, would not
be eligible for part of the Pounds 100m Konver fund.
The fund, announced in April by Mr Bruce Millan, EC regional policy
commissioner, is designed to be used for retraining, job-creation schemes
and the regeneration of disused military bases.
The Western Development Partnership, the public- and private-sector forum
which is supporting a joint bid for EC aid by Avon, Wiltshire and
Gloucestershire, said yesterday that thousands more jobs would be lost if
the Commission rejected the UK bid.
The partnership said: 'The three counties could expect to lose a further
7,000 MoD military and civilian jobs and over 12,000 from defence companies
by the year 2000 if the Konver initiative fails.'
Commission officials in Brussels yesterday signalled a willingness to accept
the UK call for flexibility on where aid could be spent, saying the funds
would reflect 'the special circumstances of the UK defence industry'.
The government outlined a six-point plan to encourage defence companies to
convert to civilian activities. This covers aid for start-up businesses;
technology transfer schemes; rehabilitation of military sites; vocational
training; joint projects to help companies diversify; and new economic
promotion agencies.
</TEXT>
