<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Link of jobs to growth queried
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICIES DESIGNED to increase the rate of economic growth in Europe will do
very little to cut unemployment, a former economics director of the Henley
Centre for Forecasting argues today.
Mr Paul Ormerod, a visiting professor at Manchester University, says the
problem of unemployment is a question 'not of economics, but of social
values and social relationships'.
The employed have operated in the European Community 'in an effective
cartel' against the unemployed.
In a paper prepared for a seminar on full employment in Europe to be held
this week in Sussex, Mr Ormerod says societies with low unemployment are
characterised by high levels of 'social cohesion'.
He pinpoints work-sharing as one valid 'technical' solution to high
unemployment, but says this would require the agreement of many people to
receive less income in exchange for more leisure.
In a challenge to 'orthodox' economic analysis - embraced by all main
political parties - which emphasises the need to generate economic growth to
bring unemployment down, Mr Ormerod argues that there is no such connection
between job creation and growth.
The US and the European Community have grown by 'almost identical' amounts
in the past 20 years, yet employment in the US is up by 45 per cent, against
only 7 per cent in Europe, he says.
The seminar - to be chaired by Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the
Commons social security committee - comes about a month after Mr David Hunt,
the employment secretary, called for a national consensus between the main
political parties on a strategy for tackling long-term unemployment.
The event will be attended both by Mr Hunt and Mr John Monks, the TUC
general secretary.
</TEXT>
