<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Japanese coalition split on priorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DIVISIONS appeared yesterday in Japan's coalition government, as Mr Morihiro
Hosokawa, the prime minister, was told by a coalition partner not to be
distracted by economic and foreign policy at the expense of political
reform.
Mr Kazuo Aichi, director of policy for the Japan Renewal party (JRP), one of
the seven coalition parties, said the government had promised to complete a
reform of the electoral system by the end of this year, and Mr Hosokawa must
devote his energies to this cause.
'The cabinet was formed to introduce political reforms. I don't think we
have the time to deal with other issues,' said Mr Aichi, replying to a
question on what changes in economic policy will be made in coming months.
His answer reflects the difference in emphasis between Mr Hosokawa and the
JRP, formed by defectors from the Liberal Democratic party, who see the
present coalition as having a mandate only to introduce electoral changes.
Some JRP officials say the coalition is intended to be temporary and oppose
the growing ambitions of Mr Hosokawa to deregulate the economy, confront
Japan's war history, and discuss a fine-tuning of US relations.
Mr Aichi suggested that Mr Hosokawa should abandon plans to address the
United Nations later this month, and spend his time thinking about political
reform. The prime minister is planning to speak on foreign policy matters.
The joint leader of the JRP, Mr Ichiro Ozawa, a former backroom operator at
the LDP, made clear that he does not expect the coalition to have a long
life by proposing that his party work towards the creation of a two-party
system.
'This (the coalition) is not the final form. The establishment of the
coalition was one step toward breaking up collusive politics, in which
politicians lie and yet manage to get away with skirting responsibility,' Mr
Ozawa said.
However, Mr Ozawa said the coalition should attempt to end the practice of
permitting bureaucrats to answer questions in parliament on behalf of
cabinet ministers, who are often not well enough prepared to discuss their
portfolio.
The coalition parties generally agree that parliamentary rules should be
changed to encourage debate.
Meanwhile, an independent MP was indicted yesterday for misrepresenting
personal details during an election campaign for the Upper House. Mr Shoji
Shinma, 58, a former radio personality, claimed that he studied at
prestigious Meiji University, but allegedly only took an entrance exam and
failed to gain admission.
</TEXT>
