FT  01 SEP 93 / Euro Disney considers rights issue to raise funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOS ANGELES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EURO DISNEY, plagued by financial problems since the opening of its theme
park outside Paris in April last year, is considering a rights issue as a
way of reviving its fortunes.
Mr Michael Eisner, chairman of Walt Disney, the US entertainment company
which is its largest shareholder, stressed in an interview with the
Financial Times that the financial restructuring of Euro Disney was still at
a preparatory stage and the two companies had not yet decided on the final
package. Euro Disney announced in July it needed to restructure its
finances.
The group is expected by analysts to make a net loss of more than FFr1.8bn
(Pounds 200m) in the financial year which ends this month, up from a loss of
FFr188m last year. Its net debt has risen from FFr18.5bn to FFr20.3bn in
this financial year.
Euro Disney's shares closed last night down 45 centimes at FFr59.95. Floated
in 1989, they have fallen 63 per cent since a record high of FFr164.30 in
March 1992.
